-## Blocked Task Handling
-
-When a task remains blocked after two failed attempts with the same failure kind, the supervisor should append a new narrow recovery task to `ppd/daemon/task-board.md` and prefer that task on the next cycle. The new task must name the exact failing guard and the expected validation command.
-
-When the narrow recovery task passes, the supervisor should reconcile the board before the next autonomous cycle:
-
-- Keep the accepted narrow task marked complete.
-- Move superseded blocked retries into Deferred Broad Items or Deferred Repair Notes as plain bullets, not checkbox tasks.
-- Append a new `[ ]` task only when there is a concrete fixture-first or validation-first next step.
-- Do not reselect an older blocked retry just because no needed tasks remain.
-
-For the current public source inventory sequence, prefer tasks with this shape:
-
-- Restore or preserve the syntax-first sentinel only.
-- Add or verify one missing committed fixture path only.
-- Add one validator behavior group at a time while keeping `validator_status()` unchanged.
-- Add a regression test for the observed supervisor failure before any live crawl or authenticated automation.
-
-## Validation Command
-
-The repair loop should use the repository PP&D validator as the supervisor-facing validation entry point:
-
-```text
-python3 ppd/tests/validate_ppd.py
-```
-
-If that validator expands into lower-level commands, syntax checks must run before unit discovery and before TypeScript checks. This keeps parser failures from being hidden behind broader test output.
+Supervisor repair proposals may edit only daemon, supervisor, validation, test, ignore, or operations documentation files allowed by the PP&D daemon policy. They must not mark domain progress by editing application artifacts, live crawl output, or DevHub private state.
